<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-112-230  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 112 230.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Feb 20 1989 v216 n8 p26(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Neighborhood fiber: putting a laser in everyone's POTS. (plain oldtelephone service)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brisk, Lloyd Frank.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Providing nearly every home in the US with a fiber-optic link tothe public telephone system is a tremendous challenge, but it isone that will be met in the early 1990s.andP;  The new distributioncables will provide millions of homes with POTS and enhancedtelecommunications services.andP;  Major obstacles to providing homeswith fiber include environmental hazards, the approval ofregulators, and cost-conscious telephone companies.andP;  Aparticularly troublesome problem is that existing copper cables doa good job of providing POTS and are capable of deliveringnarrowband enhanced services.andP;  Telephone companies will mostlikely pursue a compromise approach that uses both fiber andcopper.andP;  Such an approach might be to group houses into clustersand provide each cluster with a fiber link.andP;  Houses within thecluster would connect to the fiber via existing copper cables.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Telephone companiesFiber opticsOutlook.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>